s a characteristic feature of hyphenation rules, namely that a distinction has to be made between ‘stronger’ and ‘weaker’ rules. In the second part, he presents empirical studies which firstly – and for the first time – analyse readers’ eye movements when reading hyphenated words, and secondly analyse how primary school pupils hyphenate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGerman languagexSyllabication. 4aDeutsch. 4aSilbentrennung. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aHyphenation.  aOrthogaphy.  aReading research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2007z9783110277135oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2007z9783110276909oZDB-23-DGA0 cprintz978348430518240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311096935140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110969351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110969351/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGAb2007  aZDB-23-DGGb2007  aZDB-23-DLSc2000d2014